"Hypocalcemia"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s26_1",
"title":{
"__html":"Diagnosis"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"523223",
"children":[
"Diagnosis"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"2d126a",
"children":[
"Most cases of hypocalcemia are caused by low serum albumin levels; the ionized calcium concentration is normal. Total calcium declines by 0.8 mg/dL for each 1 g/dL decrement in serum albumin concentration."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"703286",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Symptoms and Signs"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"330511",
"children":[
"Look for:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"98f82d",
"children":[
"circumoral and acral paresthesias"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"97cebd",
"children":[
"carpopedal spasm"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"4fcec4",
"children":[
"positive Trousseau sign"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"0a165f",
"children":[
"positive Chvostek sign"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"182bf7",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Causes"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"45546e",
"children":[
"Autoimmune hypoparathyroidism (low ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"parathyroid hormone",
"children":[
"PTH"
]
},
") occurs as an isolated defect or as part of polyglandular autoimmune syndrome type 1 in association with mucocutaneous candidiasis, adrenal insufficiency, hypogonadism, and malabsorption. Hypoparathyroidism may also occur secondary to surgical excision or vascular injury to the parathyroid glands."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"409e0e",
"children":[
"In addition to hypoparathyroidism, hypocalcemia associated with elevated PTH may result from:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"a21823",
"children":[
"vitamin D deficiency"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"6cc375",
"children":[
"hypomagnesemia"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"d68d75",
"children":[
"severe pancreatitis"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"c930b8",
"children":[
"rhabdomyolysis"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"d7fe02",
"children":[
"kidney injury"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"d7c9a9",
"children":[
"tumor lysis syndrome"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"34574d",
"children":[
"Order calcium, phosphate, magnesium, creatinine, PTH, 25-hydroxyvitamin D, albumin, and/or ionized calcium tests. Order an ",
{
"type":"abbreviation",
"title":"electrocardiogram",
"children":[
"ECG"
]
},
" to evaluate for QT interval prolongation."
]
},
{
"type":"inline-wrap",
"wrapId":"1",
"contentIds":[
"mk19_bb_en_s26_inline_t1"
],
"forceOpen":true
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s26_2",
"title":{
"__html":"Treatment"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"4c4ac0",
"children":[
"Treatment"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"56a71c",
"children":[
"Treat acute symptomatic hypocalcemia with IV calcium gluconate and vitamin D. Chronic hypocalcemia is treated with oral calcium supplements and vitamin D. Choose the type of vitamin D based on the presence of underlying disease:"
]
},
{
"type":"list",
"children":[
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"8a89e9",
"children":[
"kidney disease: calcitriol (1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D)"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"06fb43",
"children":[
"liver disease: 25-hydroxycholecalciferol"
]
},
" ",
{
"type":"list-item",
"hlId":"b763a8",
"children":[
"any other cause of hypocalcemia: cholecalciferol (D",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"3"
]
},
") or ergocalciferol (D",
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"sub",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"2"
]
},
")"
]
},
" "
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"89cdfe",
"children":[
"The main adverse effect of therapy is hypercalciuria and nephrolithiasis. Correct hypomagnesemia with magnesium supplements."
]
}
]
},
{
"type":"section",
"id":"mk19_bb_en_s26_3",
"title":{
"__html":"Test Yourself"
},
"titleNode":{
"type":"section-title",
"hlId":"7866cc",
"children":[
"Test Yourself"
]
},
"children":[
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"b934af",
"class":"test",
"children":[
"A 46-year-old woman has cramps in her hands and feet. She has pernicious anemia and Hashimoto thyroiditis. Her serum calcium level is 7.9 mg/dL, and her serum phosphorus level is 4.1 mg/dL."
]
},
{
"type":"p",
"hlId":"d14817",
"class":"test_answer",
"children":[
{
"type":"tag",
"tagName":"b",
"attrs":{
},
"children":[
"Answer:"
]
},
" ",
"For diagnosis, choose autoimmune hypoparathyroidism and select a serum PTH level."
]
}
]
}
]
},
